    {
      "id": "f3dba868c0fd9e50979bf20f8db54d1a069bd686",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-06-26 13:39:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "cfe506e79516d785bea13577a3ff9a202447c392",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-26 14:08:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nInitially I agree with Alex here. Local objects have little overhead, so it makes sense to split these two different meanings into two different objects. One is a regular file with the bookmark for lfsck (MDD_LFSCK_OID), and the other is an index for object iteration (OSD_ALL_OBJECTS_OID). This allows OSD_ALL_OBJECTS_OID to be used for other reasons besides lfsck if needed in the future. \n\nOne concern is how to associate the bookmark with the index?  Does the OSD API allow the bookmark to be read into the MDD layer (as an opaque key) and the be sent back to specify the starting index?  I think yes for ldiskfs (the bookmark can just be the inode number), but I don't know if this would work for ZFS where the bookmark is an arbitrary-sized blob of data.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "45c2179706400969256b1b0ae8beab9b1eff33fc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-26 14:24:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nprobably I miss something here...\n\nI used to think bookmark is a storage where MDD (or somebody else) stores its current state (including the last processed key). this is a private data of LFSCK (or again somebody else). there might be number of features iterating objects, with own private data.\n\nobject we actually iterate is totally different - it's a virtual object, with no methods to change it. different features like LFSCK can use it.\nyou can jump into any position with ->load() method.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "db821cf481ab0413919897cc4c6ac2576dbfa993",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-26 14:47:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nRight, I thought the same thing. There might be multiple bookmarks for the iterator, so it makes sense to have separate objects for those. \n\nMy concern/question is whether the ->load() method can handle a key like a ZFS bookmark, which is a blob of opaque data (even to osd-zfs), or can it only handle simple integer keys like a hash or inode number?  If it can handle the ZFS bookmark, then any concern I have is gone, and we definitely want separate bookmark objects from the object index itself.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "d2e915a3ca9ac7438d474aae7ceca2087bc8dd29",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-06-26 14:49:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nright now we can specify 64bit hash. I think this should be enough? in the worst case we'll have to iterate few more objects, but this can happen any way as we don't sync bookmark on every scanned object?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
